<TITLE> Touching the depth of despair </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 16 (bdnews24.com) -- Familiar signs are gone. Thousands of trees are downed, as if the forest has been heavily logged. Homes stand in ruins. People have gone broke. Swapan Bepari hits the depth of despair. "The concrete walls of my house were shaking. I was scared. Usually I am a tough guy," Swapan tells bdnews24.com Friday by phone from Kaukhali Upazila in Pirojpur, one of the southern districts, hardest-hit by the super cyclone. "There was no tin-roofed house here, which did not suffer the onslaughts of the cyclone," he said. Strong winds started blowing in around 10:30pm Thursday. It took the storm just one hour to reach its fastest pace. "It was an earth-shattering experience," he said The storm that cut its devastating path through the south kicked up huge tidal surges. Swapan said: "In a matter of two minutes, the river swelled and inundated all the houses on the banks of the Kacha River. Water receded just as quickly. The area he lives in is without power. Swapan who works for the Department of Youth Development as group animator said: "I don't expect electricity to come back even in one month." bd
